<TEXT>
traffic across this 
rickety bridge has swelled as thousands of arabs stream into jordan 
for what many fear could be a final visit now that jordan has 
severed ties with the west bank 
the action by king hussein of jordan has caused widespread 
concern among palestinians that jordan will close the bridge their 
primary link to relatives in the arab world and the west banks 
major export avenue 
we have serious concerns about our future said salwa abu 
kaf of jerusalem as she left for amman with her five small children 
this week 
i am going to spend two weeks with my parents king hussein 
might decide to close the bridges and if he does it will be my 
last visit said mrs abu kaf 27 who wore a traditional 
anklelength moslem dress and scarf 
israeli officials say movement across the allenby and damiya 
bridges into jordan has increased by more than 30 percent since 
husseins july 31 announcement that he was cutting ties with arabs 
in the occupied lands 
the king scrapped a 13 billion development plan for the 
territories laid off 21200 jordanian employees in the west bank 
and gaza strip and shut a ministry for territorial affairs in his 
government jordan had maintained administrative ties even though 
israel captured the territories in 1967 
despite a pledge to keep the bridges open and honor all 
jordanian passports husseins steps raised fears among west bank 
palestinians they may no longer be allowed to travel to jordan or 
settle there as jordanian citizens 
most of the west banks 850000 palestinians and some of the 
650000 arabs who live in gaza hold jordanian passports 
twothirds of jordans 35 million people are palestinians with 
jordanian passports many with relatives in the occupied lands 
everyone carrying a jordanian passport is running scared with 
this said moussa assad a palestinian migrant farm worker in 
saudi arabia who said he crosses the bridge seven times a year to 
visit his family in gaza city 
if the king closes the bridge and takes away our passports it 
is the end for me i wont be able to travel to work to make 
money for my family many of us have no other way to survive 
said assad 41 fingering a string of flourescent green worry beads 
mohammed faiz danah of hebron said he would leave his nursing 
job in saudi arabia if the bridges were closed 
palestine is my country i have my own land my business my 
mother my sons here i am a foreigner in saudi arabia danah 
said 
some palestinians said they planned to seek residence in jordan 
so their families would not be separated 
if tomorrow they close the bridges what are we going to do 
my husband is dead i have nothing here said 63yearold hamdah 
masherehdah who said she planned to move in with her sister and 
son in amman 
pop music blared through loudspeakers tuesday as hundreds of 
palestinians streamed into the allenbys vast modern passenger 
terminal set among sand dunes just yards from the wooden plank 
bridge 
because of the increased volume israeli officials say they are 
keeping the bridges open an extra three hours each day and have 
waived the requirement that palestinians pay their taxes before 
being allowed to cross into jordan 
in the last days there has been more pressure on people to 
cross to take care of their affairs we are trying to make the 
passage easier said west bank military government spokesman 
olivier rafowicz 
some west bank businessmen expressed concern husseins measures 
may hurt palestinian exporters who rely on the bridges 
im afraid for the future if theres no way to export ill 
have to close my factory fire my 13 workers and ill be ruined 
said ahmed soubeh who owns a stonecutting firm in bethlehem that 
exports stone through jordan 
the jordanian decisions are being taken very quickly without 
prior notice this is the scary part who knows what tomorrow will 
hold we are pawns in the whole picture soubeh said 
a hebron building contractor abdulghar dufesh said west bank 
builders are owed 20 million for projects contracted by jordan 
will we be paid and when all we contractors are worried and 
wringing our hands 
