<TEXT>
summer rains in mexicos northwest have 
eased severe drought conditions in the vital agricultural and 
cattle ranching region but farm leaders say the crisis isnt over 
weve been blessed by rains it doesnt solve the problem but 
it does raise our spirits said hector roman president of the 
sonora state confederation of agriculture organizations 
a yearlong drought in mexicos northwestern grainbelt sapped 
water supplies forcing major reductions in crop plantings last 
fall and this spring in northwestern sonora and sinaloa states 
northern baja california chihuahua and coahuila states still 
are suffering effects of the drought that parched crops and turned 
pastures into barren fields 
in some areas of sonora and chihuahua the spring planting season 
was scrapped altogether as dam levels fell to less than 10 percent 
of capacity 
most affected are sorghum soybeans corn rice and wheat 
at least 660000 head of cattle have died mostly in the 
northwest because of a lack of water and feed caused by the 
drought according to an agriculture department report 
beef packers have been importing us cattle in the northwestern 
state of chihauhua for several weeks in monterrey capital of 
northeastern nuevo leon state such imports began in july under a 
governmentapproved plan to ensure supplies and keep prices down 
the damage has been done said jose antonio mendoza manager 
of the confederation of agriculture associations in sinaloa state 
he said 82 percent of more than 900000 acres normally planted with 
soybeans sorghum and rice were idled by the drought 
mendoza said the federation estimates sinaloa farmers have lost 
about 330 million in direct income 
for the first time in about 15 years sinaloa states gross 
product wont increase in fact itll fall by about 4 percent he 
said in an interview from the state capital of culiacan 
mendoza estimated about 70 percent of sinaloas productive 
sector relies on agriculture 
roman said farmers in sonoras mayo valley are scrambling to get 
government credits to buy corn seed now that rains have helped 
recoup water levels 
he said 37000 acres of corn could be planted in the coming 
weeks if the credits are approved but thats still down from the 
150000 acres normally planted in the cycle roman said 
we could be planting corn and now theres no credit said 
roman 
maria luisa elizondo an agricultural economist at the national 
bank of mexico in mexico city said rain in the northwest means 
mexico wont have to import as much wheat corn and soybean as 
feared 
but mexico still is looking at spending 300 million to 500 
million more on imported grains this year than in 1987 she said 
well have to pay more because the products will cost more 
because of the drought in the united states she said 
mendoza said it will have to rain throughout august to assure a 
good water supply for the fall planting season which begins in 
october 
were a lot more optimistic than we were a few weeks ago but 
the level of the dams still isnt sufficient to cover the 
fallwinter season he said 
what we need is a cyclone those always fill up the dams 
</TEXT>
