approval on a 1914 vote wednesday in the house education and labor 
committee the vote puts the bill in line for floor action in both 
the house and the senate where a committee approved it last month 
while senators have agreed to at least try to iron out their 
differences before bringing abc to the floor most if not all of 
the controversies aired in the house panels that considered the 
bill are expected to arise again on the house floor 
both versions of the bill authorize 25 billion next year for 
states to improve day care expand it and make it more affordable 
threequarters of the money would be used to help low and 
moderateincome families pay for child care either through vouchers 
or direct payments to providers 
while most of the money would go to the working poor states 
theoretically could give some help to households earning up to 115 
percent of the states median income over 40000 in some places 
committee democrats beat off two attempts to lower the income 
eligibility level citing political reasons among others 
in this congress programs for poor people do not fare nearly 
as well as programs that appear to benefit the middle class said 
rep stephen solarz dny by keeping open the possibility of 
help to the middle class well get the kind of support a fledgling 
program like this needs to survive 
the only significant amendment accepted wednesday lowered the 
age level of eligible children from 15 to 12 attempts to lower it 
to 7 and 10 failed 
rep tom tauke riowa leading the republican onslaught against 
the abc bill claimed it would raise unrealistic expections 
discriminate against families with a parent at home and reduce the 
supply of day care by imposing federal regulations tauke has 
introduced a rival bill revolving around family tax credits and day 
care vouchers 
he and others failed in attempts to eliminate the abc 
requirement for a commission to develop minimum federal health 
safety and training standards the standards would be mandatory for 
those day care homes and centers accepting the federal aid 
churchstate relations are another stumbling block as 
introduced the abc bill would have allowed federal funds to 
churchbased day care centers only if they did not promote 
religion they also would have had to comply with federal bans on 
religious discrimination in hiring and admissions 
the version passed by the house committee says only daycare 
slots paid for by the federal government would have to be available 
to all children regardless of religion the ban on hiring 
discrimination was dropped 
committee chairman augustus hawkins dcalif said in a 
statement after the vote wednesday that while he would prefer 
more precise language ensuring that religious indoctrination will 
not occur i support the current language at this time in order to 
move the bill forward 
he added i want to make clear that as a general proposition 
all persons should have equal access to day care programs supported 
in whole or in part by federal financial assistance 
other republican objections centered on the cost of the bill 
rep dick armey rtexas proposed authorizing 100 billion for abc 
rather than 25 billion to reflect what he called the bills 
real price tag 
were talking about megabucks he said a fiscal time 
bomb he was voted down 
rep jim jeffords rvt was the only republican to vote in 
favor of the bill wednesday two democrats pat williams of montana 
and tim penny of minnesota voted no 
