of the estimated 60000 surviving japaneseamericans who were 
affected by the 1942 internment order 
some said they planned to donate the money to charities or 
memorials to the internees others said they would share the 
taxfree cash with relatives while some wondered whether they 
would ever see the reparations 
many however said the governments apology and their restored 
honor and respect for their country meant more than the money 
president franklin d roosevelts order required all people of 
japanese ancestry living in california oregon and washington and 
some in hawaii to be relocated it affected 120000 people most 
of whom were taken to guarded camps in the south and interior west 
for former internee dorothy shundo the bill means she may no 
longer feel she has to carry her birth certificate in her purse to 
prove shes an american 
i carried it for 45 years i hope no other group of americans 
feel they have to prove their citizenship she said in the little 
tokyo district of los angeles we now know that the constitution 
is working 
ben takeshita said the payments were symbolic but important 
twentythousand dollars could not begin to compensate a person 
for his or her lost freedom for the loss of property for the loss 
of livelihood for the stigma of disloyalty takeshita said at a 
news conference at the japaneseamerican citizens league in san 
francisco 
but the 20000 means that our government is sincere in its 
apology it is a token payment yes but it is a meaningful one 
he said 
william s naito a portland ore businessman and civic 
leader was a 16yearold high school sophomore when his family was 
forced to abandon their portland gift shop and move to salt lake 
city to live with relatives he said the bills apology is 
remuneration enough 
naito recalled how disgraced he felt when he was forced to clean 
out his locker and leave school 
everyone thought i was guilty as a saboteur that i was a 
criminal that sort of thing should not happen in the united 
states of all countries he said 
dr paul hamada of hood river ore said the bill acknowledges 
the country constitutionally erred by rounding up and holding 
people who had committed no crimes 
hamada was 2 when his family was moved from his grandparents 
farm near merced calif to a camp at amache colo where they 
lived for 2 years he said he probably would donate his 
reparations to either try to perpetuate the memory of the camps 
or propagate some form of educational scholarship 
naito is working with other japaneseamericans to establish a 
memorial to the internees in portland 
i would say most of the recipients will do something like that 
with the money because they feel so strongly about it naito said 
shigeko uno 73 was interned with her family in puyallup 
wash and later in idaho the seattle resident said she might 
donate the money to a nursing home and her church but she wont 
believe it until i see it 
some may never see it 
under the bills 10year payout plan the oldest survivors some 
in their 90s will get paid first 
if youre 64 or 65 theres no guarantee youre going to live 
to 75 said 69yearold seichi hayashida president of the nampa 
idaho chapter of the japaneseamerican citizens league 
some also fear the bill will revive antijapanese feelings 
naito and others however say the vindication of the internees is 
worth the risk of further racism 
i think weve got to chance it and let the pieces fall where 
they might he said i think its important because the next 
time it might be italians the irish or whatever 
</TEXT>
