<TEXT>
the number of vietnamese boat people asking to 
be sent back home shot up during the past week after talks between 
hong kong and vietnam over largescale repatriation a government 
spokeswoman said today 
at least 90 vietnamese who fled to this british colony by boat 
have volunteered to return home including about 70 who made the 
request after last weeks talks according to the spokeswoman who 
demanded anonymity 
only 21 boat people have been voluntarily repatriated from hong 
kong since 1978 including two in july 
hong kong and vietnam officials met in hanoi to discuss 
repatriating boat people viewed by the british colony not as 
political refugees but as illegal immigrants fleeing a battered 
economy 
no agreement was reached but further talks are expected 
vietnam has said it would repatriate boat people who want to 
return home while hong kong is seeking to send back most 
vietnamese who arrived after midjune 
after the vietnam war ended in 1975 hong kong considered all 
vietnamese arriving by boat to be political refugees eligible for 
resettlement in third countries 
but under a new policy which took effect june 16 to curb the 
surging number of arrivals all incoming vietnamese are considered 
illegal immigrants subject to repatriation unless they can prove 
they fled communist vietnam because of persecution 
the spokeswoman said some of the 90 volunteers were classified 
as illegal immigrants while others were classified as refugees 
entitled to be resettled overseas she said she had no further 
details 
the repatriation applications will be forwarded to the united 
nations high commissioner for refugees to discuss with hanoi 
about 7000 vietnamese have sailed into hong kong since the new 
policy took effect bringing the number of boat people in the 
colony to about 23000 
united nations officials could not be reached for immediate 
comment 
</TEXT>
