massachusetts supreme court today ruled that a 
measure that could close the states two commercial nuclear plants 
can go on the ballot in november 
by a vote of 32 the court affirmed attorney general james 
shannons view that the question could properly be placed before 
the voters 
the high court had considered whether the ballot question if 
passed constituted an illegal taking of private property 
without compensation 
the measure would prohibit the generation of electricity by 
means which result in the production of nuclear waste after july 
4 1989 
the power plants that could be affected are boston edison cos 
pilgrim plant in plymouth and yankee atomic electric cos plant in 
rowe 
shannon had argued in court papers that the ballot question 
does not either facially or implicitly exercise the power of 
eminent domain or mandate a physical taking or invasion of private 
property 
he noted that proponents assert that the property could be 
converted to another power source used for a lowlevel waste 
repository or used for other commercial purposes 
