the earth shook a little less in the first 
half of this year 
the us geological survey reported thursday that there were 26 
significant earthquakes in the first six months of the year three 
fewer than in the same period a year ago 
and only 12 deaths have been attirbuted to quakes around the 
world in the first half of the year 
if that rate continued an annual total of 24 deaths would be 
the lowest ever recorded the survey said the current low record 
is 77 deaths in 1984 the high was 600000 in 1976 
one of this years deaths was in the united states a heart 
attack victim in california on feb 11 
of the 26 significant quakes this year only two affected the 
united states one was the feb 11 event that qualified as 
significant because of the death although it measured only 48 on 
the richter scale of ground motion 
to be considered significant a quake must cause casualties or 
measure at least 65 on the scale 
the second us quake qualified easily scoring a 76 it 
occurred march 6 in the gulf of alaska skaking parts of alaska and 
canada and generating a small tsunami or sea wave 
that was in fact the strongest quake so far this year the 
world has now gone more than 60 months without a great temblor 
measuring 80 or more 
the richter scale is a measure of the force of a quake as 
determined by ground motion an increase of one whole number from 
66 to 76 for example represents a tenfold increase in the 
strength of the quake 
