a federal judge thursday halted fall 
elections for state district court family court and court of 
appeal seats saying he found that louisianas election laws 
discriminate against black people 
attorneys for the state said they would appeal as soon as 
possible noting that the 5th us circuit court of appeal last 
week overturned a lower court injunction in a similar case dealing 
with a louisiana supreme court election 
i conceive it to be my duty having found violations to 
enjoin all district court family court and court of appeal 
elections until the governor of louisiana and the legislature have 
had an opportunity to make changes in the judicial elections system 
that will avoid such violations us district judge john parker 
wrote in thursdays order 
he specified that the state laws violate a section of the us 
voting rights act which prohibits any practice that limits voting 
rights on the basis of race 
gov buddy roemer was out of town and could not be reached 
immediately for comment 
blacks filed suit in 1986 contending that the present system 
violates federal law by diluting minority voting strength there 
are only five blacks among the 178 state district judges who 
handle most civil and criminal trials the plaintiffs said during 
recent hearings 
they had asked parker for an injunction barring the elections 
until the merits of the case could be decided their attorneys said 
thursdays order suggests that the judge will ultimately strike 
louisianas election laws dealing with the judiciary 
primary elections for various judicial seats had been scheduled 
oct 1 and runoffs if needed would have been held during the 
november general elections under louisianas open primary system 
candidates from both parties run on the same primary ballot and a 
runoff is held between the two top votegetters if no candidate 
receives a majority 
in most cases judges are elected on an atlarge basis in their 
parish the louisiana equivalent of a county or group of parishes 
rather than from singlemember districts within each parish 
the federal law requires singlemember districts blacks 
contended 
in the very near future there are going to be a significant 
number of black judges elected and the state judiciary is going to 
be significantly integrated robert mcduff lead attorney for the 
plaintiffs said after hearing of parkers injunction 
assistant attorney general ken dejean and attorney robert pugh 
handling the case for the state said they are banking on relief 
from the 5th circuit 
a federal judge in new orleans halted a louisiana supreme court 
election at the request of blacks but the 5th circuit threw out the 
injunction 
the federal appeals panel did not rule on the merits of the 
case but said that halting the election would irreparably harm the 
supreme court candidates who had already spent money on the 
campaigns 
two supreme court justices are elected at large from a 
fourparish new orleansarea district other high court districts 
in the state are singlemember districts 
the plaintiffs want at least one of the judges elected from a 
new orleansonly district where black voters are in the majority 
