soviet experts left thursday after 
winding up inspections of us cruise missiles at two sites under 
the new treaty to eliminate medium and shorterrange nuclear 
weapons 
the 20 inspectors posed for photographs and bid farewell to 
their us escorts before boarding an aeroflot flight back to 
moscow 
the inspectors arrived monday and then broke up into two teams 
to count missiles at florennes air base 40 miles south of 
brussels and the european repair facility at nearby gosselies 
it was a very good inspection characterized by a very 
cooperative spirit said us air force col john fer head of 
the us onsite inspection agencys european office at rheinmain 
air base in germany it was cordial but at the same time it was 
very professional and very well done 
the experts finished their inspections wednesday and then went 
on a tour of brussels and shopped for tshirts souvenirs 
chocolate and toys the us escorts said 
belgium is the fourth western european country the soviets have 
visited since the 60day inspection period began july 1 
fer said there are additional missile facilities in germany and 
italy that the inspectors have yet to check 
the soviets are visiting 30 sites in the united states and five 
western european countries us experts are inspecting 133 sites 
in the soviet union and eastern europe 
the inspections giving the soviets and the americans an 
unprecedented look at each others facilities can last up to 24 
hours with a possible eighthour extension 
in belgium the soviets visited florennes where us officials 
have said 16 groundlaunched cruise missiles and four spares are 
kept along with four launchers and eight spares the 485th us 
tactical missile wing is based at florennes 
there was no indication how many unarmed cruise missiles are at 
the gosselies facility which is run by the belgian defense 
contractor sabca 
on june 21 there were 55 missiles at the plant which is the 
only one in europe that maintains and repairs cruise missiles us 
officials said 
the intermediaterange nuclear forces treaty provides for 
elimination within three years of all us and soviet landbased 
missiles with ranges from about 300 to 3400 miles president 
reagan and soviet leader mikhail s gorbachev signed the treaty in 
december in washington 
