<TEXT>
doctors are becoming more concerned about ethics 
as they face complex health care issues and that concern is 
changing the way decisions are made at the patients bedside 
studies show 
doctors are turning more frequently to ethics committees or 
consultants with medical legal religious and philosophical 
expertise the journal of the american medical association said 
while the advice of such groups is not binding it gives doctors 
another perspective 
the physicians decisions must now be justified to patients 
and their families ones colleagues and the courts wrote dr 
edmund d pellegrino of the kennedy institute of ethics in 
washington in a jama editorial 
as a result every physician must know how to use the 
advice of ethical consultants wisely and well pellegrino wrote 
fridays journal devoted several articles and an editorial to 
the subject of medical ethics studies dealt with an ethics 
consultation service established at the university of chicago 
hospitals and clinics and a doctors office operated by the 
university of virginia medical center 
ethical issues are seen in cases such as that of a 55yearold 
woman who requires a machine to breathe and whose family considers 
discontinuing her treatment and the case of a 27yearold man with 
a history of drug and alochol abuse who seeks a liver transplant 
researchers led by dr julia e connelly of the university of 
virginias division of general medicine studied 280 patients who 
visited a doctors office operated by the school in charlottesville 
from november 1983 to july 1984 all the patients 212 women and 
68 men were at least 17 years old 
the researchers found that 84 of the patients or 30 percent 
presented ethical problems ranging from the issue of refusing 
treatment to issues like confidentiality and the cost of care 
the chicago study by dr john la puma of lutheran general 
hospital in suburban park ridge discussed a formal ethics 
consultation service established at the university of chicagos 
center for clinical medical ethics in 1986 members of the service 
included doctors with expertise in clinical ethics clinical ethics 
fellows and senior medical students a hospital attorney and a 
philosophy professor served as resources 
the study reviewed consultation requests over a year and found 
that 45 doctors requested consultations for 51 patients the most 
common consultation was for assistance on decisions to forego 
lifesustaining treatment la puma said 
in 71 percent of the cases the doctor found the consultation 
very important in patient management in clarifying ethical 
issues or in learning about medical ethics la puma said in 96 
percent of the cases the study found doctors indicated they 
planned to request consultations in the future 
la puma said the emphasis on ethics can help clarify medical 
issues that may have become lost in a maze of technology 
bedside ethics is what doctors and patients want and need 
he said 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

