<DOCNO> AP880811-0188 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a federal judge thursday dismissed major 
elements of a black fbi agents racial harassment lawsuit against 
the bureau as technically deficient but gave the plaintiff a chance 
to file a new complaint 
us district judge charles r richey noted that donald rochons 
lawsuit contained repugnant and chilling allegations of racial 
harassment by fellow agents 
but the judge found rochons complaint contains defects in 
both pleading and legal theory that constrain the court to dismiss 
many of the plaintiffs claims 
rochon claims he was the victim of a threeyear campaign of 
harassment by fellow agents in omaha neb and later chicago in 
which he received anonymous telephone calls and racist obscene 
letters including one that threatened him with mutilation and 
death and a sexual assault on his white wife 
gary w miller a chicago agent who was kept in the lawsuit by 
richeys order has admitted he sent rochon a death and 
dismemberment insurance policy as retribution miller is now 
the subject of a federal grand jury investigation in chicago 
the suit includes allegations that fellow agents placed 
chocolate in the earpiece of his telephone so that it came off onto 
his ear when he used the instrument 
richey chided some defendants for referring to the incidents in 
their pleadings as pranks noting that the equal employment 
opportunity commission had upheld some of rochons claims 
this utter lack of sensitivity is almost as disturbing as the 
alleged adts themselves richey said warning defendnats that a 
modicum of decency is expected of all those who file pleadings in 
this court 
the judge dismissed altogether claims against three agents with 
whom rochon worked in omaha from 1983 until his transfer to chicago 
in june 1984 ruling the threeyear statute of limitations on these 
allegations had expired 
richey refused to dismiss rochons claim against the justice 
department that as a federal employee he was a victim of 
discrimination and racial harassment in violation of title vii of 
the civil rights act of 1964 
but the judge ruled that the 21 fbi agents named in the lawsuit 
could not be sued individually under this law only the attorney 
general as head of the agency in which rochon works can be sued 
under this statute the judge said 
richey also ruled that because of the way rochons suit was 
worded his complaints of individual harassment by individual 
agents were preempted by his title vii claims and therefore could 
not be brought under other statutes 
from the imprecisely pleaded complaint it is difficult to 
discern the discrete basis of plaintiff donald rochons common law 
tort claims against individual agents richey said 
the other counts of the lawsuit are not based on distinct 
wrongs but are all based upon conduct actionable under title vii 
richey said 
but the judges dismissal of these claims without prejudice 
leaves rochons attorneys the opportunity to draft a new complaint 
to try to get around this legal obstacle 
despite the ruling rochons attorney david kairys of 
philadelphia said he was happy with the judges ruling 
he has upheld our ability to get personal damages against the 
individual wrongdoers kairys said 
kairys said he would be able to satisfy the technical 
requirements for commonlaw claims against the white agents 
although he conceded this would be more difficult against the fbi 
supervisors and managers whom rochon claims ignored his complaints 
rochons title vii claims do not allow him to collect monetary 
damages for the alleged racial harassment to do so rochon must 
sustain the claims that his constitutional rights were violated in 
distinct ways by fellow agents 
but richey found that the complaint as it was worded allowed 
the fbi agents to claim that their actions were not subject to 
legal action because they were acting in their official roles as 
government agents 
this includes allegations that rochons supervisors refused to 
investigate his charges of racial harassment 
the judge noted that the complaint states that all of the 
individual defendants with governmental positions acted within the 
scope of their employment 
given this admission that both the means used and ends sought 
by defendants were within the scope of their employment the court 
is constrained from examining the connection between the alleged 
acts and bounds of defendants official duties richey said 
under the language of the complaint these defendants are 
entitled to absolute immunity from common law tort liability 
arising out of these actions the judge said 
claims by rochons estranged wife susan also were dismissed 
without prejudice because the complaint nowhere alleges or 
even implies that defendants entered into an agreement of any 
kind to violate her civil rights 
the judge refused to dismiss commonlaw damage claims against 
miller thomas dillon and kenneth veach rochon claims that all 
three white agents orchestrated the harassment against him in 
chicago 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

