<TEXT>
american and soviet educators are spending 
two weeks coping with stereotypes and social policy in an unusual 
program aimed at teaching them new ways to tell their students 
about each others countries 
maybe first i will try them on my family joked alexander 
mitrofanovich bannov principal of a secondary school in 
novosibirsk about believing exercises and other methods 
outlined at the institute at hampshire college 
the twoweek program which began monday is sponsored by the 
soviet academy of pedagogical sciences and by educators for social 
responsibility a nonprofit organization based in cambridge 
twenty teachers researchers and administrators from each 
country were chosen for the program which is run in english 
bannov who teaches english in the high school he also 
supervises said he was surprised to find his american counterparts 
facing so many of the same problems he faced in trying to reform 
his school 
among those problems he said were the evaluation of teachers 
and students and staff and the improving of education everybody 
says teachers should teach better as if a child was a pan into 
which you could pour information like water 
lawrence dieringer associate director of esr said that for 
teachers in both countries lessons about each others country 
are fraught with problems strong feelings misinformation 
deeply embedded assumptions and resistance to new information all 
related to tensions in ussoviet relations 
thursday the participants did a believing exercise a 
method of getting students to learn how to understand other 
viewpoints by making them defend points of view they disagree with 
the teachers were asked to make statements supporting the 
position that there are some crimes so horrible and so abusive 
that they demand capital punishment 
for many participants it was impossible to suspend doubts about 
the death penalty enough to understand how others could support it 
it is very strange for me to hear about this death penalty 
said one soviet woman i cant imagine this institution 
soviet media occasionally report on executions but do not say 
how often they occur 
just last month soviet government radio reported that the state 
criminal code was being revised to eliminate the death penalty for 
all crimes except premeditated murder the current code also also 
allows death sentences for crimes such as treason and flagrant 
corruption 
earlier in the week participants discussed stereotypes each 
side believed the other held the soviets for example said they 
thought americans saw them as aggressors trying to take over the 
world dieringer said 
we thought that they thought there was a great disparity 
between the rich and poor in our country and that we dont care 
about the poor he said 
in many cases theres some kernel of truth in these 
stereotypes but they are so exaggerated and blown out of 
proportion that they serve to distort and limit our 
understanding of each other he said 
other topics being discussed are the descriptions of each 
others countries in textbooks and education reform efforts 
the idea for the teacher exchange was sparked by the 1986 tour 
of us cities by soviet academicians dieringer said the next 
institute on critical thinking will be held next summer in the 
soviet union 
