<TEXT>
once a sleeping haven for retirees in 
british colonial times bangalore today is indias version of 
silicon valley 
it manufactures about onethird of the total electronics output 
of the country and 80 percent of its professional electronics 
equipment 
r murali who quit a government job 15 years ago to set up a 
successful television component factory said bangalores 
advantages were obvious 
its a lovely city and i like the fact that its dustfree 
for many years after indias independence from britain in 1947 
bangalore was mainly a pensioners paradise known for moderate 
weather and for its lakes parks and britishstyle clubs 
situated in southern india about 200 miles inland from madras on 
the bay of bengal bangalore had one of the countrys largest 
british military populations and was the only territory directly 
ruled by london over the head of the british viceroy in india 
its temperate climate the temperature ranges from 68 to 80 
most of the year makes the city ideal but for makers of high 
technology products 
but a variety of other factors combined to make bangalore an 
upscale metropolis and one of the 10 fastest growing cities in the 
world 
industrialization in bangalore started in the early 1970s 
said vinod vyasulu a professor at bangalores institute of 
management it was brought about by the cheapest electricity 
rates in the country a readymade transport infrastructure and 
cheap skilled labor 
the number of industries in the city has risen from about 600 in 
1975 to about 2000 according to tm shirur a state government 
official at least half of them are connected with hightechnology 
manufacture he said 
labor is perhaps the most important factor for industrialists 
setting up in bangalore the citys work force largely rejected 
labor unions and strikes are rare 
michael lee an urban affairs specialist with the us agency 
for international development said bangalore is indias premier 
science city because of the availability of a pool of brains 
scientific talent is plentiful because bangalore is the home of 
the indian institute of science and the indian institute of 
management both regarded as premier schools for advanced study 
lee said 
us aid is scheduled to put up 12 million to open a center for 
technological development in bangalore it will organize training 
programs for workers and provide support services to industry 
the us company texas instruments has set up a plant and joint 
venture factories with indian firms have been formed by motorola of 
illinois and pacific intelidata of california 
indias government also has set up stateowned factories making 
electronics gear aircraft watches and telecommunication equipment 
lee compared bangalores attractions to those that drew 
electronics manufacturers to silicon valley in califonia areas in 
the us southwest and route 128 around boston 
but bangalores growth also has brought problems the population 
has risen by 76 percent over the past decade and is now estimated 
at 4 million 
residents complain that services have failed to keep pace and 
that water electricity and transport systems fall short of demand 
longtime citizens complain that bangalore is no longer the 
garden city it once was some insist the temperature is higher 
robbing bangalore of one of its attractions 
when i entered bangalore during my college vacations in the 
early 60s i used to pull on a small sweater says vijay padaki 
a teacher now based in the city now i dont use my woolens any 
more 
but a study of bangalores climate shows no appreciable change 
in air temperatures since 1870 the study concedes however that 
urbanization might have changed the microclimate which is not 
reflected in recorded temperatures 
the city looks more westernized than others in india jeans and 
tshirts are in far greater evidence than ethnic wear 
pubs are something new bangalore is the only city in india to 
have draft beer and the pubs are enormously successful india 
today magazine reported recently that city pubs sold about 35000 
mugs of beer on weekdays and double that on weekends and holidays 
the city is also home to one of the largest bookshops in india 
the gangarams book bureau which stocks 400000 english titles and 
notches up sales of 50000 rupees 3850 a day 
we get buyers from all over india said atma ram one of the 
stores two proprietors 
the cosmopolitan nature and tastes of bangalore also make it an 
ideal market to test new products new brands of shampoos soaps 
and tea are now routinely marketed in bangalore before going on 
sale in the rest of india 
</TEXT>
