many brokerages and business firms have hung huge red balloons 
imprinted with the latest stock index showing outside the buildings 
it is unbelievable said john nelson an analyst of jardine 
fleming taiwan ltd no one seems to have a good reason for this 
incredible rise 
share trading volume zoomed to 116 billion in the first seven 
months of this year a 214 percent increase from the same period 
last year 
the accumulated figure was the fourthlargest in the world after 
the tokyo new york and london exchanges according to jardine 
fleming 
many taiwan companies have set aside a fund for stock 
investments in which profits are shared with employees to prevent 
them from sneaking away from work to the brokerage floors brokers 
say 
they say some office workers even have quit their jobs figuring 
that in two weeks time playing the market they can earn more than 
their annual income which averages about 10500 
several local consulting firms forecast the stock index would 
hit 8000 or 10000 points by the end of this year 
but chen paorei an economist at the government council for 
economic planning and development recently warned share prices 
cannot continue to surge without an end the higher the prices 
rise the sharper the fall may be 
wu jungyi professor of economics of national chunghsing 
university said the overheated market is an irregular 
phenomenon that could lead to share prices falling like 
dominoes 
analysts say the latest surge began in midjuly when the ruling 
nationalist party convened a landmark congress in which it decided 
to lift import bans on major raw materials from rival mainland 
china 
the congress was quickly followed by a cabinet overhaul in which 
several aging economic officials were replaced by a younger group 
in a move seen as a precursor to reforming taiwans restrictive 
financial system 
this islands robust economic growth also is viewed as a key 
factor behind the rising share prices but analysts note that 
taiwans economic performance appears to be slowing and should not 
have boosted the market to such heights 
the government projects a 7 percent economic growth for this 
year down from the 1987 rate of 11 percent 
john chien president of the usbased federated international 
investment consulting co believes share prices have shot up 
because too many cashrich people are chasing too few stocks 
the local exchange lists only 145 companies the relatively 
small market allows manipulation by major investors who pushed 
certain share prices up before selling for huge profits analysts 
say 
another factor contributing to the overheated market is the 3 
percent daily gain and loss limit authorities imposed on share 
prices the limits designed to prevent drastic price surges or 
tumbles have prompted speculation by reducing investment risk 
analysts say 
the government in june tightened credit in an effort to dampen 
rampant stock and real estate speculation but to little effect 
credit is a little tighter but money is still abundant 
everywhere said chien 
