<TEXT>
the biggest union at pan am corp rejected a new 
labor agreement and analysts said thursday the move could spark a 
new round of conflict between labor and management at the 
financially pressed airline 
members of the transport workers union voted by a substantial 
margin to reject the contract agreed on by the unions leadership 
and pan am management on july 15 union spokesman jim gannon said 
thursday he said the final vote count was not available yet 
the union represents about 5200 mechanics aircraft service 
personnel and flight dispatchers at new yorkbased pan am the 
nations eighthlargest airline 
pan am declined to comment on the vote which dealt the airline 
a major setback in its efforts to cut labor costs the vote against 
the contract fueled speculation that pan am could revive its recent 
threat to sell a large portion of its assets 
the proposed transport workers contract had called for a wage 
freeze in return for pan am withdrawing its threat to sell assets 
the airline engaged in sporadic talks with the transport workers 
since february originally had sought a 10 percent cut in wages 
its not going to be easy said john pincavage an airline 
analyst for painewebber inc they pan am could go back to the 
old way of threatening to do different things 
speculation has been rife in recent weeks that the embattled 
carrier could target for sale its relatively profitable south 
american routes and its maintenance operations in miami and new 
york 
in a recent interview pan am chairman thomas plaskett disclosed 
that potential buyers were lined up for the international routes 
the miami repair facility and parts of pan ams maintenance 
operations in new york 
plaskett also has threatened to close down the airline if 
wage cuts and other labor concessions arent made by all the unions 
management could take a softer approach and seek concessions 
from the transport workers on work rules and other nonpay issues 
instead of the wage freeze pincavage suggested 
pan am which lost 2653 million last year believes it needs 
about 540 million over three years in pay cuts and other 
concessions to turn itself around the contract with the transport 
workers would have saved the airline about 81 million over the 
next three years according to both the union and pan am 
pan am also is seeking 90 million in wage reductions from its 
flight attendants and has imposed 35 million in cuts on employees 
represented by the teamsters union under federal labor rules the 
unions representing pilots and flight engineers agreed to cuts 
totaling about 240 million over three years 
