harcourt brace jovanovich inc the publishing 
insurance and theme park concern said thursday its secondquarter 
loss narrowed as its sales rose 235 percent from a year ago 
the company which is based in orlando fla lost 446 million 
in the three months ended june 30 compared with a loss of 708 
million in the same period a year earlier 
secondquarter revenue rose to 447 million from 362 million a 
year earlier 
the company said it had income of 222 million from publishing 
operations in the quarter compared with a loss of 41 million a 
year earlier 
it reported income of 121 million from theme park operations 
down from 143 million a year earlier its income from insurance 
operations fell to 94 million from 101 million a year earlier 
the company underwent a costly restructuring last year as it 
avoided a 2 billion takeover bid by british publisher robert 
maxwell 
its interest expense for the latest quarter rose nearly 
fivefold to 787 million from 167 million a year earlier 
before recapitalization charges the company said its operating 
income rose to 383 million for the quarter from 137 million a 
year earlier 
for the first six months of the year harcourt lost 801 
million virtually the same as its loss for the first six months of 
1987 
revenue for the first six months rose to 753 million from 647 
million a year earlier 
